{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477152"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:58:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:58:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14188"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14188"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.66,0.04,0.03,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55777"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6871"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14188"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41322"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1514"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2922"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55777"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent due to frequent urinary tract infections (UTIs). She has had five UTIs in the past year, each treated with antibiotics. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine microscopy: \u0026gt;100 white blood cells per high-power field\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine culture: \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E \u0026gt;10^5 colony-forming units/mL\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum creatinine: 60 \u00b5mol/L (30-80)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely long-term complication if this condition is left untreated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal tubular acidosis","Chronic kidney disease","Renal cell carcinoma","Polycystic kidney disease","Nephrotic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a young girl with recurrent urinary tract infections (UTIs), which raises concern for an underlying urological abnormality, most likely vesicoureteral reflux (VUR). VUR is a condition where urine flows backwards from the bladder into the ureters and sometimes to the kidneys. If left untreated, this can lead to significant long-term complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely long-term complication in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic kidney disease (CKD)\u003C/strong\u003E. Recurrent UTIs in the presence of VUR can cause repeated kidney infections, leading to ongoing inflammation and scarring of the kidney tissue over time. This condition is known as reflux nephropathy. The repeated damage to the kidneys can eventually result in chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrotic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, and oedema. While it can occur in children, it is not typically associated with recurrent UTIs or VUR. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of kidney cancer that primarily affects adults and is not associated with childhood UTIs or VUR. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder characterised by the growth of numerous cysts in the kidneys. It is not caused by or related to recurrent UTIs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal tubular acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the kidneys fail to acidify the urine adequately. While it can be associated with some kidney diseases, it is not a typical complication of recurrent UTIs or VUR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s history of recurrent UTIs, it is crucial to investigate for VUR. This typically involves a renal ultrasound and a voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG). Early detection and management of VUR, which may include antibiotic prophylaxis or surgical correction in severe cases, is essential to prevent long-term renal damage and the development of CKD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while the current serum creatinine is within normal limits, this does not rule out the possibility of developing CKD in the future if the underlying condition is left untreated. Regular monitoring of renal function and appropriate management are key to preventing long-term complications in children with recurrent UTIs and suspected VUR.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recurrent urinary tract infections in children can be a sign of vesicoureteral reflux, which may lead to reflux nephropathy and chronic kidney disease.","Early detection and management of vesicoureteral reflux is crucial to prevent long-term renal damage.","Vesicoureteral reflux is a common cause of recurrent urinary tract infections in children."],"references":["Aeddula NR, Baradhi KM. Reflux Nephropathy. In: StatPearls. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526055/","Lee SY, Lai JN, Haw Y, Chiu LT, Huang SM, Cheng KL, Chew FY. Vesicoureteral reflux is associated with increased risk of chronic kidney disease: A nationwide cohort study. Medicine (Baltimore). 2023 Aug 25;102(34):e34867. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10470671/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41322"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14188"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41322"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T20:54:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T20:54:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6871"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55777"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta